1. if you are following the XORT/README to install this package, your 
environment should be set up properly. However, you can always add
path of this package to your PERLLIB if you install somewhere other
than the default (since you need administrator permission to install
in the default location). For example, if you install XORT to
/export/xort, then you can add it to PERL5LIB with following command:

For example, if you check out from cvs into this directory:
/home/scott/schema/XMLTools/XML/XORT and then install xort into
/export/xort (via the command `perl Makefile.PL`, 
then you pub /export/xort when ask where to install XORT,
even I just notice in MAC that it will add to perl library directory,
then you don't need to worry about this ),
then add the following line to .cshrc file:

  setenv PERL5LIB /export/xort

or for bash-likes:

  export PERL5LIB=/export/xort


2. We understand that different projects may work on different version of 
chado schema. xort come with a utility to get this around. (For FlyBase
project, XORT already comes with default the ddl.properties
file, so you can skip this step). To create the ddl.properties file
( basically this converts the ddl file with which you create database
into some property file used by XORT modules. For chado, this will be
the ddl file: conf/chado.ddl)

  bin/ddl_properties_creator.pl `-d <ddl file> [-v <view file> -h]`

It will create property file: conf/ddl.properties

Notice: 
  If you have some views/functions which are specific to your project,
and you want the XORT modules to RECOGNIZE them (if you have views,
but just want to ignore it, then -v is optional). For example, you 
may also want to dump views into ChadoXML, or want to load some xml
file with view data inside, or you want to diff two chado xml files
with and without view data, you need to MAKE one create TABLE statement
for each view/function in another file (see the sample file
conf/function_view.sql and function_view.ddl). This is what the
ddl_properties_creator.pl -v argument is for. 

examples: 
We have this view for the FlyBase project:

CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW prediction_evidence (
  prediction_evidence_id, 
  feature_id, 
  evidence_id, 
  analysis_id
) AS 
  SELECT anchor.feature_id||':'||evloc.feature_id||':'||af.analysis_id, 
         anchor.feature_id, 
         evloc.feature_id, 
         af.analysis_id
  FROM featureloc anchor, featureloc evloc, analysisfeature af
  WHERE anchor.srcfeature_id = evloc.srcfeature_id 
    AND evloc.feature_id     = af.feature_id 
    AND ((evloc.fmin>=anchor.fmin AND 
          evloc.fmax<=anchor.fmax) OR 
         (evloc.fmin<=anchor.fmin AND 
          evloc.fmax>=anchor.fmax) OR
         (evloc.fmin<=anchor.fmax AND 
          evloc.fmax>=anchor.fmax) OR 
         (evloc.fmin<=anchor.fmin AND 
          evloc.fmax>=anchor.fmin));

If we want to dump/load/diff chado xml with prediction_evidence using XORT,
I will create this view.ddl:

create table prediction_evidence (
   prediction_evidence_id varchar(50) not null,
   primary key (prediction_evidence_id), 
   feature_id int not null,
   foreign key (feature_id) references feature (feature_id),
   evidence_id int not null,
   foreign key (evidence_id) references feature (feature_id),
   analysis_id int not null,
   foreign key (analysis_id) references analysis (analysis_id),
   unique (feature_id, evidence_id, analysis_id)
);

Then XORT tools will treat this view:prediction_evidence the same as any other table.

We also recognize the needness of multiple DB schema instance, for all executable files under bin, 
they have option '-y' to pinpoint which version of DB schema to use instead of default schema

3. Besides installing the XORT executables, the installation steps also collect
 database information which will be written to a very important configuration 
file called chado.properties (default location: XML-XORT/conf/chado.properties).
  The chado.properties file contains all the necessary information for XORT to
 connect to the chado database you are working with.  If at some point you 
need to connect to a different instance of chado on your postgres server, 
you can either edit the chado.properties file to indicate the new chado 
database name, or create a new file, with suffix '.properties' (e.g.
"my_new_chado.properties").    In order to be used by XORT, any '.properties'
file needs to be located in the configuration directory (/home/work/XML-XORT/conf/).
When executing XORT (see below), the -d parameter specifies which 'properties'
file to use (e.g. "-d my_new_chado").

This file contains all the necessary information for the database 
connection, e.g my_new_chado.properties contains:

db_type=postgres
db=chado_gadfly8
host=gonzalez.flybase.harvard.edu
port=5432
user=zhou
password=*******

and for any script that requires a -d argument, one would supply
"-d my_new_chado".

