10. Understand content in chado XML format
     The hierarchical structure of XML documents is idea for
 mimicking the object relationships inside a relational database
 schema. Mapping of XML elements to tables/columns truthfully 
reflects the table/column and primary/foreign key relationships,
 given the fact that a relational database schema can be 
represented by a unique DTD. Therefore, XML possesses a great
 advantage for automatic processing of large-scale biological
 data, e.g. genome sequence data.
     Pinglei Zhou and Stan Letovsky at FlyBase Harvard 
(Zhou et al, 2005) have developed a specification for mapping
 relational database schema into XML document. Initially started
 with chado schema, therefore this XML structure has been named
 as chado XML, even though it can be applied to any schema
 as long as the schema satisfies certain constraints, which
 are: all primary keys are serial numbers, and each table 
has unique key(s). Unique key is the only way to represent
 a unique record out of database environment since primary 
key is meaningless if outside of the database context. All table
 names are XML elements, so are all table's columns which are 
nested within their own table elements. Primary table and 
foreign table relationship is translated into outer and inner
 elements relationship, with foreign table elements nested 
inside primary table elements and after the primary table'  
column elements. Softwares for mapping database schema into DTD
 has been developed, not only achieving the mapping, but also 
preserving all the database schema information into a property 
file, which will be used as guide for all other activities. 
     From data structure's point of view, XML is tree. A chado
 database becomes a tree when converted into XML, with the root
 node being chado, the non-leaf node being either table node, 
which means the label of node is one of table names, or column 
node, which means the label of node is one of the column names 
of the corresponding database table. Direct children of root 
node are table nodes, nodes of a table node could be either 
column node, or table node if the child table node have foreign
 key referring to the parent node's primary key. For example,
 node of feature could be uniquename which is a column of 
feature, or featureprop because of the fact that featureprop
 has feature_id column referring to the primary key of 
feature:feature_id. Child of column node could be either leaf
 node with no label but only content of the column, or table 
node whose children node represent the content of this column
 node if this column node is also foreign key node. 


